  <section class="morph-highlights" id="morph-highlights-section" aria-labelledby="morph-highlights-title">
    <h2 id="morph-highlights-title" class="morph-highlights-title">Five ideas from the chapter</h2>
    <p class="morph-highlights-intro">
      Tap a card for a short preview; tap again to expand full notes. These ideas match the chapter and the trees above.
    </p>
    <div class="morph-highlight-grid" role="list">
      <article class="morph-highlight-card" data-morph-hl-card role="listitem">
        <button
          type="button"
          class="morph-highlight-card__toggle"
          data-morph-hl-toggle
          id="morph-hl-t-1"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="morph-hl-p-1"
        >
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__badge" aria-hidden="true">1</span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__head">
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__title">Morpheme</span>
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__teaser"
              >The smallest unit with a meaning or a grammatical function—not the same as a syllable.</span>
          </span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        </button>
        <div
          class="morph-highlight-card__panel"
          id="morph-hl-p-1"
          data-morph-hl-panel
          role="region"
          aria-labelledby="morph-hl-t-1"
          hidden
        >
          <div class="morph-highlight-card__prose">
            <p>
              &ldquo;The smallest unit with a meaning or a grammatical function&rdquo; (Park-Johnson &amp; Shin, 2020.)
            </p>
            <p>
              Not to be confused with syllables; which are the most basic unit of spoken language consisting of an
              uninterrupted sound before being broken up with another vowel sound.
            </p>
            <p>
              Words can have one morpheme. Referred to as simple words, they cannot be broken down any further.<br />
              Examples: &ldquo;good&rdquo;, &ldquo;happy&rdquo;, &ldquo;video&rdquo;
            </p>
            <p>
              Words can also be formed by using two or more morphemes to create words with added layers of definition.
              These are called complex words.<br />
              Examples: &ldquo;teacher&rdquo;, &ldquo;reconstruction&rdquo;
            </p>
            <p>The word &ldquo;teacher&rdquo; is created using morphemes &ldquo;teach&rdquo; and &ldquo;er&rdquo;.</p>
            <p>
              &ldquo;teach&rdquo; (instruct) + &ldquo;er&rdquo; (person that does an action) = &ldquo;teacher&rdquo;
              (person that instructs)
            </p>
            <p>The word &ldquo;reconstruction&rdquo; is created using multiple morphemes.</p>
            <p>
              &ldquo;re&rdquo; (again) + &ldquo;con&rdquo; (with) + &ldquo;struct&rdquo; (build) + &ldquo;ion&rdquo;
              (process) = &ldquo;reconstruction&rdquo; (the process of building together again.)
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="morph-highlight-card" data-morph-hl-card role="listitem">
        <button
          type="button"
          class="morph-highlight-card__toggle"
          data-morph-hl-toggle
          id="morph-hl-t-2"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="morph-hl-p-2"
        >
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__badge" aria-hidden="true">2</span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__head">
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__title">Roots and affixes</span>
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__teaser"
              >The root carries the core meaning; affixes attach before (prefix) or after (suffix); words can also
              compound.</span>
          </span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        </button>
        <div
          class="morph-highlight-card__panel"
          id="morph-hl-p-2"
          data-morph-hl-panel
          role="region"
          aria-labelledby="morph-hl-t-2"
          hidden
        >
          <div class="morph-highlight-card__prose">
            <p>
              The root, a category of simple words, is the morpheme that carries the core meaning of a word and cannot be
              broken down any further.<br />
              (Example: collect)
            </p>
            <p>
              Affixes are a type of morpheme that can attach to a root, either directly before or right after the root.
            </p>
            <p>
              If the affix is attached ahead of the root, it is known as a prefix.<br />
              Example: &ldquo;re&rdquo; (prefix) + &ldquo;collect&rdquo; (root) = &ldquo;recollect&rdquo;
            </p>
            <p>
              If the affix is attached after the root, it is known as a suffix.<br />
              Example: &ldquo;collect&rdquo; (root) + &ldquo;ion&rdquo; (suffix) = &ldquo;collection&rdquo;
            </p>
            <p>
              Words can be made up using more than one affix.<br />
              Example: &ldquo;re&rdquo; (prefix) + &ldquo;collect&rdquo; (root) + &ldquo;ion&rdquo; (suffix) =
              &ldquo;recollection&rdquo;
            </p>
            <p>
              Words can also be composed of two words joined together. These are called compounds.<br />
              Example: &ldquo;white&rdquo; (adjective) + &ldquo;board&rdquo; (noun) = &ldquo;whiteboard&rdquo; (noun)
            </p>
            <p>
              Compounds can take the form of words directly joining together to create a new word (i.e. whiteboard,
              bedroom).<br />
              A hyphen may be used to create a compound (i.e. gluten-free, twenty-one)<br />
              Compounds may also be created by having a space between two words (i.e. school bus, pet friendly, customer
              service).
            </p>
            <p>
              Their status as a noun, verb, adjective, or adverb is determined by the second word in the compound.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="morph-highlight-card" data-morph-hl-card role="listitem">
        <button
          type="button"
          class="morph-highlight-card__toggle"
          data-morph-hl-toggle
          id="morph-hl-t-3"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="morph-hl-p-3"
        >
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__badge" aria-hidden="true">3</span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__head">
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__title">Free, bound, content, function</span>
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__teaser"
              >Free morphemes stand alone; bound morphemes must attach; content vs function morphemes do different jobs in
              sentences.</span>
          </span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        </button>
        <div
          class="morph-highlight-card__panel"
          id="morph-hl-p-3"
          data-morph-hl-panel
          role="region"
          aria-labelledby="morph-hl-t-3"
          hidden
        >
          <div class="morph-highlight-card__prose">
            <p><strong>Free morphemes</strong></p>
            <p>Definition: A morpheme that can stand alone as a word</p>
            <p>Most roots in English are free morphemes</p>
            <p><strong>Bound morphemes.</strong></p>
            <p>Definition: A morpheme that can only occur in words attached to other morphemes.</p>
            <p>Examples</p>
            <p>
              Prefixes: un- (unhappy), re- (redo)<br />
              Suffixes: -ed (walked), -s (cats)<br />
              Roots Like -mit (submit, permit) or -ept (inept) are also bound
            </p>
            <p>Bound morphemes can be further divided into derivational morphemes and inflectional morphemes</p>
            <p><strong>Content morphemes</strong></p>
            <p>Definition: Morphemes that carry meaning as opposed to only performing a grammatical function</p>
            <p>Content Morphemes constitute major part of vocabulary</p>
            <p>
              Nouns: cat, trees, street, envy<br />
              Verbs: go, run, play,state<br />
              Adjectives: Big,small, nice<br />
              Adverbs: fast, often, very
            </p>
            <p>
              Content morphemes constitute what called an open class where new words are often introduce<br />
              Example of words: download, Realtime, hyperlink
            </p>
            <p><strong>Function Morphemes</strong></p>
            <p>Definition: Morphemes that provide information about the grammatical relationship between words in a sentence</p>
            <p>Example:</p>
            <p>
              Articles; the, a, an<br />
              Conjunctions: and, or, but, so<br />
              Prepositions: in, on, above, beside<br />
              Pronouns: I, me, you, he, she, their
            </p>
            <p>
              Function morphemes constitute what is called a Closed class in which set of words is fixed and rarely changes
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="morph-highlight-card" data-morph-hl-card role="listitem">
        <button
          type="button"
          class="morph-highlight-card__toggle"
          data-morph-hl-toggle
          id="morph-hl-t-4"
          aria-expanded="false"
          aria-controls="morph-hl-p-4"
        >
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__badge" aria-hidden="true">4</span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__head">
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__title">Derivation vs. inflection</span>
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__teaser"
              >Derivational affixes build new words; inflectional suffixes mark grammar and stay on the outer edge.</span>
          </span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        </button>
        <div
          class="morph-highlight-card__panel"
          id="morph-hl-p-4"
          data-morph-hl-panel
          role="region"
          aria-labelledby="morph-hl-t-4"
          hidden
        >
          <div class="morph-highlight-card__prose">
            <p><strong>Derivational Morphemes</strong></p>
            <p>Definition: morphemes that change either the meaning or the part of speech of the word</p>
            <p>What makes Deviation different from Inflection?</p>
            <p>
              Change the part of speech or the meaning of a word<br />
              -ment in Statement<br />
              Are not required by syntax<br />
              Are selective about what they can combine with<br />
              Are typically attached before inflectional Suffixes<br />
              -ment in Statement -s must be added before the -s
            </p>
            <p>Examples:</p>
            <p>
              Suffixes<br />
              -al, -ize, - ness, -ship as in friendship<br />
              Prefixes:<br />
              Re-, un-,dis-,inter as in rewrite
            </p>
            <p><strong>Inflection Morphemes</strong></p>
            <p>Definition: Affixes that are added to a word to assign a specific grammatical property to that word</p>
            <p>What Makes Inflection Different from Derivation?</p>
            <p>
              Do not change the part of speech or the meaning of a word<br />
              Are required by Syntax<br />
              It typically occurs with all members of some large class of morphemes<br />
              Occur at the Margin of a word<br />
              There is only 8 in English language and all of them are Suffixes
            </p>
            <p>Adjectives</p>
            <p>
              Comparative - er<br />
              Superlative - er
            </p>
            <p>Verbs</p>
            <p>
              3rd person singular - s<br />
              Progressive - ing<br />
              Past tense - ed<br />
              Past participate -en/-ed
            </p>
            <p>Nouns</p>
            <p>
              Plural - s<br />
              Possesive- s
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="morph-highlight-card" data-morph-hl-card role="listitem">
        <button
          type="button"
          class="morph-highlight-card__toggle"
