          <span class="morph-highlight-card__badge" aria-hidden="true">5</span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__head">
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__title">Allomorphs, analysis, teaching</span>
            <span class="morph-highlight-card__teaser"
              >Morphemes have predictable surface variants; structure can differ even when spelling matches.</span>
          </span>
          <span class="morph-highlight-card__chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        </button>
        <div
          class="morph-highlight-card__panel"
          id="morph-hl-p-5"
          data-morph-hl-panel
          role="region"
          aria-labelledby="morph-hl-t-5"
          hidden
        >
          <div class="morph-highlight-card__prose">
            <p><strong>Allomorphs</strong></p>
            <p>An allomorph is a variation of a morpheme that still keeps the same meaning.</p>
            <p>The form changes depending on the linguistic environment (sounds around it).</p>
            <p>Examples</p>
            <p>
              Plural -s:<br />
              /s/ → cats<br />
              /z/ → dogs<br />
              /ɪz/ → buses<br />
              Past tense -ed:<br />
              /t/ → walked<br />
              /d/ → played<br />
              /ɪd/ → wanted
            </p>
            <p><strong>Analysis</strong></p>
            <p>Allomorphs are predictable variants of a morpheme.</p>
            <p>The variation depends on the phonological environment (surrounding sounds).</p>
            <p>
              Example: plural and past tense endings change sound but keep the same grammatical meaning.<br />
              Speakers often know these patterns subconsciously.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Teaching</strong></p>
            <p>
              Teach allomorphs by showing patterns (word families) so students recognize changes.<br />
              Make affix meanings explicit so students connect form → meaning.<br />
              Use examples like -s and -ed to help students see predictable pronunciation changes.<br />
              Focus on helping learners notice patterns in new vocabulary.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
    <p class="morph-source-line">
      <strong>Source:</strong> Park-Johnson, S., &amp; Shin, S. J. (2020). <em>Linguistics for Language Teachers</em>.
      Taylor &amp; Francis. ·
      <strong>Further reading:</strong> Aronoff, M., &amp; Fudeman, K. (2010). <em>What is morphology?</em> (2nd ed.).
      Wiley-Blackwell.
    </p>
